[1] Stripe rust - USA: Pacific Northwest, new strain suspected
Date: Wed 6 Jul 2011
Source: Flathead Beacon [edited]
http://www.flatheadbeacon.com/articles/article/disease_sweeps_over_wheat_fields/23760/


Disease sweeps over wheat fields
--------------------------------
Exacerbated by cool and damp weather, a fungal disease called stripe
rust has spread across the Pacific Northwest's croplands, threatening
significant losses in wheat during a growing season that began with
high hopes for above-average yields.

Farmers in Montana and neighboring states have been forced to spend
many thousands of dollars on fungicide to combat what a wheat producer
says is the worst outbreak of stripe rust he's experienced.

Bob Stougaard, Montana State University, wonders if it's a new
strain. Research plants at his nursery that had previously proven
fairly resistant are experiencing "high infection" this year [2011].
He described the rust as "epic."

"I suspect we might have a new race in the area," he said. "If we do,
varieties that were rated as resistant or tolerant may not have that
type of classification and we have to look for new varieties to grow
in this area."

[Byline: Myers Reece]

