[2] Foot rot - UK
Date: Tue 5 Jul 2011
Source: Farmers Weekly Interactive [edited]
http://www.fwi.co.uk/Articles/2011/07/05/127658/Wheat-foot-rot-takes-advantage-of-dry-season.htm


Wheat foot rot takes advantage of dry season
--------------------------------------------
An aggressive fusarium foot rot infection has killed a number of
wheat plants in drought-stressed parts of the eastern counties. The
damage has been caused by the common _Fusarium culmorum_ fungus,
normally associated with ear blight. But because some crops have been
subjected to significant drought stress, the fungus has been able to
take hold, said Bill Clark, Broom's Barn. "It only manifests itself
under very high soil moisture deficits."

The disease is more common in North America, it is particularly rare
for it to appear in UK, he said. "Under normal conditions, the fungus
isn't aggressive enough to kill the plant."

Affected fields have scattered white heads and the symptoms can be
mistaken for ear blight, take-all, or eyespot, said Caroline Nicholls,
HGCA [Home Grown Cereals Authority]. But the stem base appears water
soaked and dark brown, while lower nodes can be pinkish under active
sporulation. There is no effective treatment this [2011] season, but
growers should consider ploughing down trash if infections are severe
to prevent build up of inoculum for next season, she suggested.

[Byline: Mike Abram]

