[Stripe rust
------------
Stripe rust (also called yellow rust) of cereals is caused by the
fungus _Puccinia striiformis_ var. _striiformis_. The disease affects
wheat, some barley varieties, triticale, and a number of wild grasses.
It causes yellow leaf stripes and stunting of plants with yield losses
of 40 to 100 percent.

Spores are wind dispersed in several cycles during the cropping
season and the fungus survives on living host plants generating a
"green bridge" between seasons. Disease management includes the use of
resistant varieties, fungicide applications, and control of volunteer
crops.

New stripe rust strains with increased virulence are emerging
worldwide. In the US, a new strain was reported for example in 2010
(ProMED-mail post 20100510.1522). Monitoring and resistance breeding
programmes have been established in different wheat growing regions.

Foot rot
--------
Several species of the soil- and residue-borne fungal genus
_Fusarium_ are causing a number of head blight, stalk rot, seedling
root rot, and ear and stalk rot diseases in grain crops such as maize,
wheat, barley, rye, and oats. In parts of northern Europe, _F.
culmorum_ and _F. avenaceum_ are the prevalent pathogens. These fungi
persist and multiply on infected crop residues. Spores are spread by
wind, rain splash, and with contaminated materials. Stress conditions,
such as the drought reported in item 2 above, and lesions caused by
other fungi or insects are known to increase susceptibility of host
plants to _Fusarium_.

_Fusarium_ species, including _F. culmorum_, are capable of producing
mycotoxins which can affect livestock. However, for root infections
causing foot rot as reported above, toxins may be less likely to be
present in the harvested grain. Disease management for _Fusarium_ may
include cultural techniques (such as crop rotation, ploughing in of
contaminated crop residue as mentioned above), crop varieties with
increased levels of resistance, and fungicides for affected above
ground plant parts.

